<DOC><DOCNO> AP880926-0211 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 2254EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Peru     09-26 0278</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Peru,0286</SECOND><HEAD>Five Soldiers Killed in Peruvian Guerrilla Ambush</HEAD><DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Maoist rebels ambushed an army truck in thehighlands Monday and killed five soldiers and wounded six in acrossfire after crippling the vehicle with land mines, police said.   Also Monday, the military command in Ayacucho state said an armypatrol killed two rebels in a clash with a column of Shining Pathguerrillas Sept. 20.   The ambush Monday occurred on a lonely mountain road 27 mileseast of Huancavelica, a state capital 155 miles southeast of Lima.   Police said rebels had mined a 100-yard stretch of dirt roadwith dynamite every 10 yards and that at least nine chargesexploded as the truck passed.   A lieutenant and four soldiers were killed. Eight soldiers whoescaped harm and some of the six wounded troops managed to repelthe attack and the Shining Path guerrillas withdrew after half anhour, according to the police report.   Police said the rebels were believed to have suffered casualtiesbut took their wounded with them.   In Ayacucho, a state capital 70 miles southeast of Huancavelicaand 230 miles southeast of Lima, the military command said a patrolencountered a rebel column on Sept. 20, killing two guerrillas inthe ensuing firefight.   A military communique said troops captured arms, grenades andsubversive pamphlets in the shootout but that other members of theguerrilla force escaped. The communique did not say if the patrolsuffered casualties.   The impoverished countryside around Ayacucho was the birthplaceeight years of the Mao-inspired Shining Path insurgency.   Since then the violence has spread through much of the countryand more than 12,000 people have been killed.</TEXT></DOC>